21
00:00:53,385 --> 00:00:55,010
That's the next thing
that I'd probably

22
00:00:55,010 --> 00:00:56,960
say if I needed
something or if I

23
00:00:56,960 --> 00:00:58,460
was going to leverage
the Cloud, I'd

24
00:00:58,460 --> 00:01:01,530
probably end up using Lambda
for something before, honestly,

25
00:01:01,530 --> 00:01:03,530
a lot of the other tools
we've even seen so far.

26
00:01:03,530 --> 00:01:06,030
And again, that's obviously
given my background and the type

27
00:01:06,030 --> 00:01:07,790
of projects I'm
working on, but it's

28
00:01:07,790 --> 00:01:11,030
such a versatile and useful
tool that I want you to see it.

29
00:01:11,030 --> 00:01:13,260
So let's just dive
into it right away

30
00:01:13,260 --> 00:01:17,130
so we can get some context
for why it is so valuable.

31
00:01:17,130 --> 00:01:20,190
So at a high level,
as I mentioned before,

32
00:01:20,190 --> 00:01:22,980
Lambda is a serverless
compute service.

33
00:01:22,980 --> 00:01:27,350
So what that means is that I am
not spinning up EC2 instances

34
00:01:27,350 --> 00:01:28,230
explicitly.

35
00:01:28,230 --> 00:01:32,090
I'm not actually determining
the amount of resources

36
00:01:32,090 --> 00:01:34,020
I need to do a specific task.

37
00:01:34,020 --> 00:01:37,190
I basically just define my code.

38
00:01:37,190 --> 00:01:39,930
I come up with the code
for my task at hand.

39
00:01:39,930 --> 00:01:41,970
I upload it to
the Lambda service

40
00:01:41,970 --> 00:01:43,800
or basically I create
a Lambda function,

41
00:01:43,800 --> 00:01:46,080
which houses my code in it.

42
00:01:46,080 --> 00:01:49,310
And then either
based off of events

43
00:01:49,310 --> 00:01:51,690
or I can run on a
schedule every night,

44
00:01:51,690 --> 00:01:54,980
every day, whatever it is,
I will kick off this lambda

45
00:01:54,980 --> 00:01:57,240
function and then
it'll just run it.

46
00:01:57,240 --> 00:01:59,300
So to me as a user,
I actually don't even

47
00:01:59,300 --> 00:02:02,110
have to think about this
as a Cloud infrastructure

48
00:02:02,110 --> 00:02:02,860
that's being used.

49
00:02:02,860 --> 00:02:03,985
How much time is it taking?

50
00:02:03,985 --> 00:02:05,470
I don't worry about that at all.

51
00:02:05,470 --> 00:02:07,930
All I think about is
I want this task done.

52
00:02:07,930 --> 00:02:10,000
And I don't want to
do it on my computer.

53
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:11,710
Therefore, I write
the Lambda function,

54
00:02:11,710 --> 00:02:14,880
deploy it there, and it
runs at the pace that I need

55
00:02:14,880 --> 00:02:18,540
or on the schedule that I need
or for the events that I need.

56
00:02:18,540 --> 00:02:22,020
That level of
hands off is really

57
00:02:22,020 --> 00:02:25,107
what again can start to make
the Cloud such a useful tool.

58
00:02:25,107 --> 00:02:27,190
The more that we have to
get in the weeds with it,

59
00:02:27,190 --> 00:02:28,847
the less valuable
it starts to become,

60
00:02:28,847 --> 00:02:31,180
the more headaches we have
debugging and all that stuff,

61
00:02:31,180 --> 00:02:32,380
as you all have seen.

62
00:02:32,380 --> 00:02:35,700
But I just want to try to get us
or introduce us to these tools.

63
00:02:35,700 --> 00:02:39,270
Anytime you see a
serverless service, that

64
00:02:39,270 --> 00:02:41,010
is what we're really
talking about,

65
00:02:41,010 --> 00:02:44,340
is you're removing all of that
management away from yourself.

66
00:02:44,340 --> 00:02:48,250
So again, upload your code,
deploy a Lambda function,

67
00:02:48,250 --> 00:02:50,790
runs on a schedule or
in response to events.

68
00:02:50,790 --> 00:02:52,270
Only runs when it's triggered.

69
00:02:52,270 --> 00:02:55,333
And again, you only pay
for the time that you use.

70
00:02:55,333 --> 00:02:58,000
So if you're not using any-- if
you're not running the function,

71
00:02:58,000 --> 00:02:59,042
you're not paying for it.

72
00:02:59,042 --> 00:03:01,270
It's not like something
where, with the EC2 instance,

73
00:03:01,270 --> 00:03:03,150
if I have it up, I have to
remember to stop it and all that

74
00:03:03,150 --> 00:03:04,270
or terminate it.

75
00:03:04,270 --> 00:03:05,620
None of that matters.

76
00:03:05,620 --> 00:03:07,440
I only pay for it
when I'm using it.

77
00:03:07,440 --> 00:03:09,690
So I can just set up the
function, deploy it, and then

78
00:03:09,690 --> 00:03:11,160
I don't have to worry that
I'm all of a sudden running up

79
00:03:11,160 --> 00:03:13,200
the cost, unless I'm
triggering a bunch of events

80
00:03:13,200 --> 00:03:14,742
or if there's a
bunch of computations

81
00:03:14,742 --> 00:03:17,010
that have to be done.

82
00:03:17,010 --> 00:03:19,710
So as far as pros
and cons go then,

83
00:03:19,710 --> 00:03:22,038
pros by far one of the
best things about it

84
00:03:22,038 --> 00:03:24,580
is that it supports multiple
different programming languages.

85
00:03:24,580 --> 00:03:25,500
So we're going to
use it obviously

86
00:03:25,500 --> 00:03:27,792
in Python, given that that's
what we teach for the most

87
00:03:27,792 --> 00:03:28,950
part in our department.

88
00:03:28,950 --> 00:03:33,378
But it encompasses a bunch
of other tools and languages

89
00:03:33,378 --> 00:03:34,920
or better statement
can work directly

90
00:03:34,920 --> 00:03:36,820
with those other languages too.

91
00:03:36,820 --> 00:03:40,530
So if you're coding in C++, you
can just deploy your function

92
00:03:40,530 --> 00:03:41,798
directly in that language.

93
00:03:41,798 --> 00:03:43,590
You don't to rewrite
it into something else

94
00:03:43,590 --> 00:03:44,590
or worry about that.

95
00:03:44,590 --> 00:03:47,890
It just knows how to
interpret that language.

96
00:03:47,890 --> 00:03:49,910
And I don't have the exact
list, but if you just

97
00:03:49,910 --> 00:03:52,327
go to Lambda site, you'll see
obviously the listing there.

98
00:03:52,327 --> 00:03:54,390
And we'll see when we
do a demo of what we

99
00:03:54,390 --> 00:03:57,000
have available for ourselves.

100
00:03:57,000 --> 00:03:58,740
The other thing
again is completely

101
00:03:58,740 --> 00:04:00,100
automated administration.

102
00:04:00,100 --> 00:04:02,340
So we don't have to worry
about it, like being

103
00:04:02,340 --> 00:04:03,840
the admins of our
services, we don't

104
00:04:03,840 --> 00:04:07,060
have to start anything like
that, worry about instances.

105
00:04:07,060 --> 00:04:09,240
It just handles itself.

106
00:04:09,240 --> 00:04:10,930
Built-in fault tolerance.

107
00:04:10,930 --> 00:04:13,260
So it's doing these
computations itself

108
00:04:13,260 --> 00:04:15,390
across multiple
availability zones

109
00:04:15,390 --> 00:04:18,540
to protect against any sort
of individual machine or data

110
00:04:18,540 --> 00:04:19,630
center failures.

111
00:04:19,630 --> 00:04:23,110
So when I kick off my Lambda
function, unbeknownst to me,

112
00:04:23,110 --> 00:04:25,530
it's going to be running
in multiple locations

113
00:04:25,530 --> 00:04:27,910
so that I can avoid
any of those risks.

114
00:04:27,910 --> 00:04:32,440
So again, completely
managed serverless service.

115
00:04:32,440 --> 00:04:35,790
You're not worrying
about any of that at all.

116
00:04:35,790 --> 00:04:38,278
You can orchestrate multiple
functions as well too.

117
00:04:38,278 --> 00:04:40,570
So you can have one function
kick off another function.

118
00:04:40,570 --> 00:04:42,237
They can sync up and
do things together.

119
00:04:42,237 --> 00:04:46,085
So very flexible toolkit that
again, we pay per usage for.

120
00:04:46,085 --> 00:04:47,460
So it's billed in
increments of I

121
00:04:47,460 --> 00:04:49,870
think milliseconds or
something like that.

122
00:04:49,870 --> 00:04:53,730
So again, we're only going to be
paying for exactly what we need.

123
00:04:53,730 --> 00:04:55,650
Actually, for that
matter, we could

124
00:04:55,650 --> 00:04:58,300
and we'll pull it up in a
second here the pricing on that.

125
00:04:58,300 --> 00:05:02,680
But that is kind of the
consideration for it.

126
00:05:02,680 --> 00:05:06,910
Now, as far as cons go,
everything has downsides.

127
00:05:06,910 --> 00:05:09,490
For one, it's not really--

128
00:05:09,490 --> 00:05:10,390
I don't want to say--

129
00:05:10,390 --> 00:05:12,250
I think not suitable for
small projects is maybe

130
00:05:12,250 --> 00:05:13,460
a bit harsh of a statement.

131
00:05:13,460 --> 00:05:16,580
It's just that it's a little
bit overkill for small projects.

132
00:05:16,580 --> 00:05:19,120
Like we'll see, for example,
when we build our own Lambda

133
00:05:19,120 --> 00:05:21,777
functions, if I'm just
doing something one time,

134
00:05:21,777 --> 00:05:23,860
I don't really need to
worry about being scheduled

135
00:05:23,860 --> 00:05:24,910
or something like that.

136
00:05:24,910 --> 00:05:26,990
It's not really worth setting
up as a Lambda function.

137
00:05:26,990 --> 00:05:29,198
It's going to take me just
as much time to create it,

138
00:05:29,198 --> 00:05:31,510
debug it as it would to
just spin up an EC2 instance

139
00:05:31,510 --> 00:05:32,660
and do the task.

140
00:05:32,660 --> 00:05:36,040
So instead, I really want to
keep these reserved for cases

141
00:05:36,040 --> 00:05:38,440
where I need to do something
at scale or in a way

142
00:05:38,440 --> 00:05:40,885
that I really am going to be
repeating this process over

143
00:05:40,885 --> 00:05:41,510
and over again.

144
00:05:41,510 --> 00:05:45,340
I don't want to have to
manage that orchestration.

145
00:05:45,340 --> 00:05:48,802
You'll also need
to know in advance,

146
00:05:48,802 --> 00:05:50,510
or at least that may
be a debugging step.

147
00:05:50,510 --> 00:05:54,760
And actually in preparation
for one of the future demos,

148
00:05:54,760 --> 00:05:57,070
I forgot this
point, but you need

149
00:05:57,070 --> 00:05:59,570
to have a sense of the memory
needs of your function.

150
00:05:59,570 --> 00:06:01,520
So when we deploy
this function, it's

151
00:06:01,520 --> 00:06:05,330
going to have a set minimum
or maximum memory like RAM

152
00:06:05,330 --> 00:06:06,860
that it utilizes.

153
00:06:06,860 --> 00:06:08,730
And also it'll have
a timeout command.

154
00:06:08,730 --> 00:06:11,523
So if it runs for I think
longer than a few seconds,

155
00:06:11,523 --> 00:06:13,190
it'll just assume
that maybe it's broken

156
00:06:13,190 --> 00:06:15,590
and I should shut it down,
such that I'm not charging you

157
00:06:15,590 --> 00:06:17,370
for all the seconds
that it's live.

158
00:06:17,370 --> 00:06:19,127
And that's a great
feature to have.

159
00:06:19,127 --> 00:06:21,710
But also if my function actually
does take a long time to run,

160
00:06:21,710 --> 00:06:23,880
like I know it's going to
take on the order of minutes,

161
00:06:23,880 --> 00:06:25,630
I need to make sure I
give it the capacity

162
00:06:25,630 --> 00:06:28,950
to be able to run for minutes
so that I don't have that issue.

163
00:06:28,950 --> 00:06:30,680
Now, the risk is
obviously if I set it

164
00:06:30,680 --> 00:06:34,050
for just infinite amount of
time as far as the timeout,

165
00:06:34,050 --> 00:06:36,350
then I could be
charged continuously

166
00:06:36,350 --> 00:06:38,610
for something that could
quickly run up in costs.

167
00:06:38,610 --> 00:06:42,920
So that balancing act
is necessary still.

168
00:06:42,920 --> 00:06:46,333
And then finally, you are
still constrained to only run

169
00:06:46,333 --> 00:06:47,250
your commands in code.

170
00:06:47,250 --> 00:06:50,270
So you can't-- and this
is easily behind my head.

171
00:06:50,270 --> 00:06:52,260
You couldn't just go
and say, OK, well,

172
00:06:52,260 --> 00:06:54,685
I need to do something
in Microsoft Word

173
00:06:54,685 --> 00:06:56,810
and grab that and upload
it or something like that.

174
00:06:56,810 --> 00:06:58,790
You're not going
to be orchestrating

175
00:06:58,790 --> 00:07:03,490
or being able to tie together a
bunch of external applications.

176
00:07:03,490 --> 00:07:05,688
Everything you do is
going to be in code.

177
00:07:05,688 --> 00:07:07,730
So if it's something where
you're still learning,

178
00:07:07,730 --> 00:07:09,820
you're kind of going through the
process of understanding Python,

179
00:07:09,820 --> 00:07:12,670
how to code in Python, this
might not be the tool for you

180
00:07:12,670 --> 00:07:13,460
yet.

181
00:07:13,460 --> 00:07:15,580
But as you start to
understand a coding language

182
00:07:15,580 --> 00:07:17,658
or if you have that
experience, then this

183
00:07:17,658 --> 00:07:18,950
can be a really great resource.

184
00:07:18,950 --> 00:07:21,650
But again, you will need
to do everything in code.

185
00:07:21,650 --> 00:07:23,096
So considerations.

186
00:07:25,720 --> 00:07:29,380
So then as far as what can
trigger a Lambda function,

187
00:07:29,380 --> 00:07:32,810
I think first off, the easiest
to explain is not listed here,

188
00:07:32,810 --> 00:07:35,350
but the easiest to understand
would be just using

189
00:07:35,350 --> 00:07:40,810
some sort of schedule, is if I
have a scheduled event that--

190
00:07:40,810 --> 00:07:42,310
and we'll see how
to set that up,

191
00:07:42,310 --> 00:07:45,550
where every night it has to
run or every 10 seconds I need

192
00:07:45,550 --> 00:07:49,880
to run or maybe every day
at 3:00 and 5:00 PM it runs,

193
00:07:49,880 --> 00:07:51,470
that is the easiest one to do.

194
00:07:51,470 --> 00:07:53,210
And it basically will
send off an alert.

195
00:07:53,210 --> 00:07:57,100
And I believe it uses
Amazon's EventBridge service

196
00:07:57,100 --> 00:07:59,210
to kick off those events.

197
00:07:59,210 --> 00:08:02,160
And that will trigger-- or that
can trigger a Lambda function.

198
00:08:02,160 --> 00:08:06,020
So you can set it up such that
it triggers on the schedule.

199
00:08:06,020 --> 00:08:08,120
But I think arguably
more interesting

200
00:08:08,120 --> 00:08:10,680
are all the other ways that
we can trigger a function.

201
00:08:10,680 --> 00:08:13,530
So for example, entry
into an S3 bucket.

202
00:08:13,530 --> 00:08:17,270
So upload, deletion, moving
of a file, any of those things

203
00:08:17,270 --> 00:08:19,200
can technically
send off a trigger.

204
00:08:19,200 --> 00:08:21,680
Meaning that again,
if somebody maybe

205
00:08:21,680 --> 00:08:24,260
uploads a file to my S3 bucket.

206
00:08:24,260 --> 00:08:25,460
Maybe you guys are students.

207
00:08:25,460 --> 00:08:27,210
Maybe if we did this,
and I could do this,

208
00:08:27,210 --> 00:08:29,490
for example, for a project.

209
00:08:29,490 --> 00:08:32,700
Maybe I say when you are
done with your assignment,

210
00:08:32,700 --> 00:08:34,559
upload it to this S3 bucket.

211
00:08:34,559 --> 00:08:36,409
And then every
time the S3 bucket

212
00:08:36,409 --> 00:08:40,820
gets a new file into there,
I could trigger an AWS Lambda

213
00:08:40,820 --> 00:08:45,332
function that would then
maybe go and check to see if--

214
00:08:45,332 --> 00:08:47,040
and let's tie this
into machine learning.

215
00:08:47,040 --> 00:08:49,610
Maybe it would look to see
if your screenshot looks

216
00:08:49,610 --> 00:08:53,590
like the screenshot of
a A, B, a C, or a D.

217
00:08:53,590 --> 00:08:56,413
And it classifies A, B, C, or D.

218
00:08:56,413 --> 00:08:58,580
I could set up a function
that does that, assuming I

219
00:08:58,580 --> 00:09:01,080
have trained a model that
can make that prediction.

220
00:09:01,080 --> 00:09:03,260
But let's imagine we
have this magic black box

221
00:09:03,260 --> 00:09:06,080
that taking as input a
screenshot of your website

222
00:09:06,080 --> 00:09:07,670
can predict the grade.

223
00:09:07,670 --> 00:09:09,890
Well, then maybe I
could, again, when

224
00:09:09,890 --> 00:09:12,200
you upload your file
to the S3 bucket,

225
00:09:12,200 --> 00:09:14,040
it triggers my Lambda function.

226
00:09:14,040 --> 00:09:21,110
It runs and it immediately
scores your assignment,

227
00:09:21,110 --> 00:09:25,953
and then returns to me a JSON
file or maybe pushes it to--

228
00:09:25,953 --> 00:09:27,870
the Lambda function is
again just Python code.

229
00:09:27,870 --> 00:09:30,083
So I could have a
push to a database.

230
00:09:30,083 --> 00:09:32,000
I could probably even
find a way to sync it up

231
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:34,670
with Canvas honestly, such
that Canvas automatically

232
00:09:34,670 --> 00:09:35,970
gets an uploaded grade.

233
00:09:35,970 --> 00:09:38,150
So all these things are
now at your disposal.

234
00:09:38,150 --> 00:09:40,050
Anything you can think
about piping together,

235
00:09:40,050 --> 00:09:43,790
as long as you can do it
in code, you can do it.

236
00:09:43,790 --> 00:09:48,110
And again, it can be triggered
by S3 bucket actions.

237
00:09:48,110 --> 00:09:51,360
Similarly, insertions
in a DynamoDB table.

238
00:09:51,360 --> 00:09:53,940
So DynamoDB is a NoSQL database.

239
00:09:53,940 --> 00:09:56,540
So if some of the adds,
updates, deletes data

240
00:09:56,540 --> 00:09:58,320
in this database, same thing.

241
00:09:58,320 --> 00:09:59,862
I can trigger an
AWS Lambda function.

242
00:09:59,862 --> 00:10:01,862
And again, this is assuming
everything's running

243
00:10:01,862 --> 00:10:02,520
